The relationship between task measures and the two symptom factors (regression analysis)


In this script, the relationship between the task measures derived from the Facial Expression Recognition Task and symptom factors are analysed. The task measures are analysed individually using multiple linear regression. Scores for the two factors Anxiety-Depression and Anhedonia-Apathy are included as predictors of interest. To control for age, gender and education, these variables are added as additional regressors. To control for task performance, a general measure of task performance is included as additional regressor.

The task measures include: - Unbiased Hit Rate for each emotion (a measure for how often each emotion was correctly identified) - Reaction times - Positive bias for Unbiased Hit Rate and reaction times, i.e. the extent to which participants were more accurate or faster for positive compared to negative emotions


# Settings for Stan/BRMS
niter=8000
nchains=4
adaptdeltas=0.9


Regression analyses for Unbiased Hit Rate (UHR)


# Mean unbiased hit rate across emotions (will be used as control regressor)

UHR_mean_across_emotions <-brm(formula = FERT_UHR_mean_across_emotions ~ AnxietyDepression + AnhedoniaApathy +
                 Age + Gender + mo(Education), data=all,family='gaussian',iter=niter,chains=nchains,cores=nchains,
                 control=list(adapt_delta=adaptdeltas))
#summary(UHR_mean_across_emotions)

# Unbiased hit rate ###########################################################################################

# "raw" hit rate, controlled for mean hit rate ("FERT_UHR_mean_across_emotions")
UHR_happy_c <-brm(formula = FERT_UHR_happy ~ AnxietyDepression + AnhedoniaApathy + 
                Age + Gender + mo(Education) + FERT_UHR_mean_across_emotions,     
                data=all,family='gaussian',iter=niter,chains=nchains,cores=nchains,
                control=list(adapt_delta=adaptdeltas))
#summary(UHR_happy_c) 

UHR_surprise_c <-brm(formula = FERT_UHR_surprise ~ AnxietyDepression + AnhedoniaApathy + 
                Age + Gender + mo(Education) + FERT_UHR_mean_across_emotions,     
                data=all,family='gaussian',iter=niter,chains=nchains,cores=nchains,
                control=list(adapt_delta=adaptdeltas))
#summary(UHR_surprise_c) 

UHR_sad_c <-brm(formula = FERT_UHR_sad ~ AnxietyDepression + AnhedoniaApathy +

                data=all,family='gaussian',iter=niter,chains=nchains,cores=nchains,
                control=list(adapt_delta=adaptdeltas))
#summary(UHR_sad_c)

UHR_fear_c <-brm(formula = FERT_UHR_fear ~ AnxietyDepression + AnhedoniaApathy + 
                Age + Gender + mo(Education) + FERT_UHR_mean_across_emotions,     
                data=all,family='gaussian',iter=niter,chains=nchains,cores=nchains,

#summary(UHR_fear_c)

# Unbiased hit rate positive bias

Extract regression coefficients


# Unbiased Hit Rate (UHR)

UHR_mean_across_emotions_est <- summary(UHR_mean_across_emotions)
UHR_mean_across_emotions_est <- UHR_mean_across_emotions_est$fixed
UHR_mean_across_emotions_est$Parameter <- "UHR_mean_across_emotions"

UHR_happy_est <- summary(UHR_happy_c)
UHR_happy_est <- UHR_happy_est$fixed
UHR_happy_est$Parameter <- "UHR_happy"

UHR_surprise_est <- summary(UHR_surprise_c)
UHR_surprise_est <- UHR_surprise_est$fixed
UHR_surprise_est$Parameter <- "UHR_surprise"

UHR_sad_est <- summary(UHR_sad_c)

UHR_fear_est <- summary(UHR_fear_c)

UHR_anger_est <- summary(UHR_anger_c)

Unbiased_hit_rate_positive_bias_log_est$Parameter <- "Unbiased_hit_rate_positive_bias_log"

# RT

Plot regression weights for Anxiety-Depression


FERT_AnxietyDepression <- rbind(UHR_happy_est[2,], UHR_surprise_est[2,], UHR_sad_est[2,], UHR_fear_est[2,], UHR_anger_est[2,], UHR_disgust_est[2,],  Unbiased_hit_rate_positive_bias_log_est[2,], RT_happy_est[2,], RT_surprise_est[2,], RT_sad_est[2,], RT_fear_est[2,], RT_anger_est[2,], RT_disgust_est[2,], Positive_bias_RT_log_est[2,])

FERT_AnxietyDepression$Parameter[FERT_AnxietyDepression$Parameter=="Unbiased_hit_rate_positive_bias_log"] <- "UHR_positive_bias_log"

FERT_AnxietyDepression$Parameter <- factor(FERT_AnxietyDepression$Parameter, levels = c("UHR_positive_bias_log","UHR_happy", "UHR_surprise",
                                                                                        "UHR_sad","UHR_fear","UHR_anger", "UHR_disgust", "Positive_bias_RT_log",
                                                                                        "RT_happy","RT_surprise", "RT_sad", "RT_fear","RT_anger", "RT_disgust"))


FERT_AnxietyDepression$ParameterFERT_AnxietyDepression$sig <- F
FERT_AnxietyDepression$sig[(FERT_AnxietyDepression$`l-95% CI` > 0  & FERT_AnxietyDepression$`u-95% CI` > 0 )| (FERT_AnxietyDepression$`l-95% CI` < 0 & FERT_AnxietyDepression$`u-95% CI` < 0)] <- T
FERT_AnxietyDepression$Task <- "FERT"

ggplot(data=FERT_AnxietyDepression)+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, colour = "grey")+
  geom_errorbar(aes(reorder(Parameter, desc(Parameter)), ymin = `l-95% CI`, ymax = `u-95% CI`, colour = sig), size=1, width=0)+
  geom_point(aes(Parameter, Estimate, colour = sig), size=3)+
  theme(text = element_text(size = 14))+
  scale_colour_manual("legend",values=c("TRUE"="blue","FALSE"="grey50"))+
  theme(legend.position="none",panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(), axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"))+
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("FERT - AnxietyDepression regression weights")


Anxiety-Depression score significantly predicted a positive bias in the Unbaised Hit Rate. Individuals with higher Anxiety-Depression scores showed a less pronounced bias towards positive emotions.

Anhedonia-Apathy scores did not significantly predict any task measure. This indicates that the relationship with the positive bias in the Unbiased Hit Rate was specific to Anxiety-Depression symptoms.
